			    STPJS 322</div>
  <p class="std">If I have sinned, I have sinned outwardly; but surely I have contemplated the things of God.<span class="footRef">1</span></p>
  <p class="std">Respecting the Melchizedek Priesthood, the sectarians never professed to have it; consequently
  they never could save any one, and would all be damned together.<span class="footRef">2</span> There was an Episcopal priest
  who said he had the priesthood of Aaron,<span class="footRef">3</span> but had not the priesthood of Melchizedek:<span class="footRef">4</span> and I bear
  testimony that I never have found the man who claimed the Priesthood of Melchizedek. The power
  of the Melchizedek Priesthood<span class="footRef">5</span> is to have the power of &ldquo;endless<span class="footRef">6</span> lives&rdquo;;<span class="footRef">7</span> for the everlasting
  covenant<span class="footRef">8</span> cannot be broken.<span class="footRef">9</span></p>
  <p class="std">The law was given under Aaron<span class="footRef">10</span> for the purpose of pouring out judgments<span class="footRef">11</span> and destructions.</p>
  <p class="wideEllipse">* * *</p>
  <div class="topic">Three Grand Orders</div>
  <p class="std">There are three grand orders of priesthood<span class="footRef">12</span> referred to here.</p>
  <p class="std">1st. The King of Shiloam (Salem)<span class="footRef">13</span> had power and authority over that of Abraham,<span class="footRef">14</span> holding
  the key and the power of endless life.<span class="footRef">15</span> Angels desire to look into it, but they have set up too many
  stakes.<span class="footRef">16</span> God cursed the children of Israel<span class="footRef">17</span> because they would not receive the last law from
  Moses.<span class="footRef">18</span></p>
  <p class="std">The sacrifice required of Abraham<span class="footRef">19</span> in the offering up of Isaac,<span class="footRef">20</span> shows that if a man would
  attain to the keys of the kingdom of an endless life;<span class="footRef">21</span> he must sacrifice all things.<span class="footRef">22</span> When God offers
  a blessing or knowledge to a man, and he refuses to receive it,<span class="footRef">23</span> he will be damned. The Israelites
  prayed that God would speak to Moses and not to them;<span class="footRef">24</span> in consequence of which he cursed them
  with a carnal law.<span class="footRef">25</span></p>
  <p class="std">What was the power of Melchizedek?<span class="footRef">26</span> &rsquo;Twas not the Priesthood of Aaron which administers
  in outward ordinances,<span class="footRef">27</span> and the offering of sacrifices.<span class="footRef">28</span> Those holding the fulness of the
  Melchizedek Priesthood<span class="footRef">29</span> are kings and priests<span class="footRef">30</span> of the Most High God,<span class="footRef">31</span> holding the keys of power
  and blessings.<span class="footRef">32</span> In fact, that Priesthood is a perfect law<span class="footRef">33</span> of theocracy, and stands as God to give
  laws to the people, administering<span class="footRef">34</span> endless<span class="footRef">35</span> lives<span class="footRef">36</span> to the sons and daughters of Adam.<span class="footRef">37</span></p>
